tribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lever  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Lever","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname for a fleet-footed or timid person, from Old French <i>levre</i> ‘hare’ (from Latin <i>lepus</i>, genitive <i>leporis</i>). It may also have been a metonymic occupational name for a hunter of hares.","English: topographic name for someone who lived in a place thickly grown with rushes, from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed, iris’. Compare   Laver  . Great and Little Lever in Greater Manchester are named with this word (in a collective sense), so the surname may also be a habitational name from these places.","Dutch and North German: from the medieval personal names <i>Lever</i>, a variant of <i>Liever</i> (see   Lieber  ), and <i>Levert</i>, a variant of <i>Lievert</i> (see   Liebhart  ). This surname is very rare in Germany."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record wit